Day 1

General instructions

To answer the questions in this practice sheet:

  1. Open week-7-practice.R located in the code/ sub-folder and set the working directory to its location. In RStudio,

    Session > Set Working Directory > To Source File Location

  2. Apply the code you saw in the demonstration scripts and pre-recorded demonstration videos to answer the questions below.

By completing the tasks in this document, you will practice with:

  • diagnostic tools for model (mis)specificaion;
  • diagnostic tools for assumptions related to the residuals;
  • computation of robustness standard errors;
  • influential observations.

You will need only the following dataset:

  • airQual.rds stored in the data/ sub-folder

2 Part 1: Visualization & Modeling

These assignments are about a study on the popularity of highschool students. A total of 246 students from 12 different classes took part in this study in which we determined how extraversion, gender, and teacher experience influenced a students popularity.

The data for the 12 different classes are stored in de the dataframes Class1 - Class12. The dataframe Total contains the combined data of all classes.

List of all the variables:

  • pupil: pupil identification variable

  • class: class identification variable

  • student-level independent variables: Extraversion (continuous; higher scores mean higher extraversion) and Gender (dichotomous; 0 = male, 1 = female)

  • class-level independent variables: teacher experience teacherExp in years

  • outcome variable: Popular (continuous: higher scores indicate higher popularity).

2.1 - Assignment 1: Inspection

Lets look at descriptives, visualize our data, and check assumptions for relevant variables. For simplicity, well only look at the variables Extraversion, Popular, and Gender (but feel free to play around with the other variables too). Well first select only those variables and store them in a dataframe called subset which well run our visualization on.

  • Check the datatype of all variables and see if they are correct. Which variable do you need to change?

  • Check distributions and scatterlots of the relevant variables. Do they look okay?

  • Run an initial linear model with Popular as the DV and Extraversion and Gender as the IVs, and check the model using the check_model command (note that we dont look at model parameters yet, since we do not yet know if this model is really appropriate). Note that we can get more information about influential cases and outliers by asking for this info explicitly using $INFLUENTIAL and $OUTLIERS after the check_model output object. Do we have to account for heteroscedasticity?

  • Also check model assumptions when Extraversion is entered as an ordinal variable. Do the diagnostics improve?

2.1.6 - Model assumptions with Extraversion as ordinal variable

Regr1_o <- lm(Popular ~ 1 + ordered(Extraversion) + Gender, data = Total)        
check_model(Regr1_o)

We decide to go for the regression model with Extraversion as a continuous variable, because entering Extraversion as ordinal did not improve diagnostics much (see the lecture for more info). However, homogeneity was not great for this data. As such we might opt to use robust SEs using the vcovHC command. Using the HC covariance matrix covHC0, you can go ahead and investigate the coefficients of Regr1 with robust SEs.

2.1.7 - Accounting of heteroscedasticity

covHC0 <- vcovHC(Regr1)

2.2 - Assignment 2: Modeling Heteroscedasticity

We could also deal with the heteroscedasticity in our data by actually modeling it. This is easy to do with Bayesian analysis. Lets assume that we expect based on visualization or prior knowledge that higher extraversion is associated with lower variability in popularity. In other words, the heterogeneity is based on Extraversion.

  • Run a Bayesian analysis without correction for heteroscedasticity and compare the results to the frequentist results. Do the results differ?
  • Run a Bayesian analysis, where you model the dependence of the residual variance, sigma, on Extraversion. Since youre basically doing two regression analyses, one to predict the mean of Popular and one to predict the SD (or the variance sigma), you combine both the models in one object using the bf command. What is the effect of Extraversion on sigma? Do the parameter estimates differ compared to the frequentist results?

3 Part 2: Nested Data

Lets continue with the data on the popularity of highschool students. But now well start exploring and incorporating the nested nature of the data. The data of this study show a clear hierarchy - or nesting - , with students nested in classes. Since observations of students from the same class are most likely not independent, we cant just analyse these data using normal linear regression. In addition, we are dealing with variables on different levels. We have pupil level variables like Extraversion and Gender, but we also have class characteristics like teacher experience. We can estimate both types of variables in a single analysis only when using multilevel analysis. In this assignment, well start with some regular regression analyses on the data of each separate class separately because this will help you get the hang of R, but also because it will make the multilevel analyses more insightful. Then, given the hierarchical nature of the data, we run a multilevel regression analysis on the complete data.

List of all the variables:

  • pupil: pupil identification variable

  • class: class identification variable

  • student-level independent variables: Extraversion (continuous; higher scores mean higher extraversion) and Gender (dichotomous; 0 = male, 1 = female)

  • class-level independent variables: teacher experience teacherExp in years

  • outcome variable: Popular (continuous: higher scores indicate higher popularity).

You see that the mean estimates across the separate analyses are not identical to the multilevel estimates. This is because multilevel analysis assumes that the inter-class differences in the intercept and coefficients are normally distributed, whereas the estimates from the separate analyses dont impose a distribution on the individual estimates. As a result, the multilevel estimates are pulled towards the mean parameter values across classes.
